NYC Taxis Trips Demand Prediction

Weihan Li

May 4, 2019

Introduction

Dataset

The dataset contains trip by trip data for NYC taxis in 2018, including fields capturing pick-up and drop-off dates/times, pick-up and drop-off locations, trip distances, itemized fares, rate types, payment types, and driver-reported passenger counts.

Project suggestion

  1. Find important features of the demand for taxis, like daily cycles and weekly cycles.
  2. Predict the amount of demand for taxis in a particular area

Why its meaningful

  1. The same method can be applied to ride-sharing companies like Uber/Lyft to forecast demand. Demand prediction can be used to make pricing decisions to balance supply and demand.

  2. For taxi companies, they can use this forecast to reduce labor cost by having more drivers work on the peak hours and fewer drivers work on the off-peak hours.

Data Exploration And Visualization

The whole dataset is around 9.7GB, for illustration purposes, Ill only use part of it to show some exploratory analysis. We aggregate the data into 15-minutes interval and extract some time features from the timestamp. The features considered here are year, month, week, day, hour, weekday, hour of week and whether its a businessday.

Day Trend

Do people take taxis on Friday as frequent as Monday? The intuitive answer is no. lets see what the data says. The chart below shows the average number of trips per weekday and weekend

As we can see, number of trips keeps increasing from Monday to Friday, and falling back during the weekend. Sunday and Monday has the lowest trips and Friday has the highest trips. Is there any specific reason for such pattern?

The next plot shows the average hourly trips in a week from Monday 00:00 am to Sunday 11:59pm.

With this plot, things become clear.

For each day, we have a morning peak around 8 AM and an evening peak around 6 PM. and The variance for peak hours(8 AM to 10 PM) is pretty high, which means its harder for us to predict peak hours than to predict off-peak hours( 11 PM to 7 AM), this will be showed in later prediction model.

The daily pattern is very simlar during weekdays, but its very different between weekdays and weekends. On Saturday and Sunday, we dont see a spike during evening peak hour, because people dont need to take taxis home after work as they do on weekdays.

Non-businessday includes weekends and holidays, lets see the difference between businessday and non-businessday.

Hourly Trend

For non-businessday,

  1. We dont see the morning peak aound 8 AM, because people dont need to go to work.

  2. We still see a eveing peak around 7 PM. Probably people are taking taxi to the dinner or party.

  3. We see a spike at 0 AM, one explanation is that most people are drunk after the party and have to take a taxi home.

The businessday trend matches with the previous observation. The morning peak is around 8 AM and the evening peak is around 19:00 PM. Since Most of the days are businessday, the overall trend is very close to businessday trend.

So far, we have found below features are pretty important for us to predict the demand: Weekday, hour, whether its a business day and month. But first, lets take a look at the number of trips itself as a time-series data with frequency equals to 7 days. Here is the autocovariance function(based on 15-minutes interval)

As we can see, demand(number of trips) is highly correlated with itself at 1 lag(15 minutes ago), 96 lag(1 day ago), 192 lag(2 day ago)
If we order it by the correlation, well have

  1. lag 1 (15 minutes)

  2. lag 96 (1 day)

  3. lag 672 (1 week)

  4. lag 192 (2 days)

Modeling

Here lets try to predict with the random forest first. Random forest (RF) requires very little time to optimize. It is robust to the outliers, irrelevant variables, countinuous and discrete variables. Ill use the RF to predict the number of logins, then use its partial dependence plots and variable importance plot to get the insights about how it got information from the variables.

First, lets try using RF to predict the number of logins for next 3 days

We can see that hour is the most important feature here. As we mentioned above, peak hours have high variance which is hard to predict,Our basic RF model is underfitting the data, so here we can do some tricks to improve the result significantly,

  1. Use SVM instead of RF(test result shows SVM performs better here).

  2. For each hour, build a different SVM model, so we need to trian 24 SVM model. Peak hour and Off-peak hour has totally different behavior, its reasonable to train them seperatly.

  3. Add another feature, total demand for current hour. We will use ARIMA model to predict total demand for that specific hour first and feed this predicted number into our SVM model.

With this new approach, features we feed into the model are

  1. weekday

  2. month

  3. hour

  4. is_businessday

  5. lagged demand
  • lag1(15 minutes)
  • lag96(1 day)
  • lag192(2days)
  • lag762(1 week)
  1. current hour demand(predicted)
